<p class="center small">✧  From Tidewater to the Upland South  ✧</p>

<p>
  As opportunities shifted in Virginia, new possibilities opened in the forests and hills
  beyond the settled Tidewater. Land in the Carolinas, Tennessee, Georgia, and Kentucky
  beckoned settlers with the promise of space and independence. This was the world that
  would shape two more of John’s paternal lines: the Brittain and Rhyne families.
</p>

<p>
  The Brittain family, of Welsh origin, came to be associated with the Southern frontier.
  In the early nineteenth century, one figure in particular stands out as a marker of this
  line’s character: Burrell Brittain, born in 1785 and a veteran of the War of 1812. His
  headstone, naming him as a soldier in that conflict, symbolizes a tradition of service
  and loyalty to the young United States. It also places the Brittain line squarely in the
  generation that saw the frontier push from the older colonies into the interior South.
</p>

